
[1]casuistry

   CASUISTRY, n. The science or doctrine of cases of conscience; the
   science of resolving cases of doubtful propriety, or of determining the
   lawfulness or unlawfulness of what a man may do, by rules and
   principles drawn from the scriptures, from the laws of society, or from
   equity and natural reason.

   Casus foederia. The case stipulated by treaty; that which comes within
   the terms of compact.
